section.section:
"Historic provider", to the extent the provider meets the requirements in paragraph (1) of this subsection, shall include:
A federal or State qualified community health center;
A provider with a program for the training of health care professionals, including an academic medical center;
A hospital outpatient program, physician, or advanced practice nurse that is a Maryland Access to Care (MAC) provider;
A local health department;
A hospice, as defined in Title 19, Subtitle 9 of this article;
A pharmacy; and
Any other historic provider designated in accordance with regulations adopted by the Department.

text.section:
"Ombudsman program" means a program that assists enrollees in resolving disputes with managed care organizations in a timely manner and that is responsible, at a minimum, for the following functions:
Investigating disputes between enrollees and managed care organizations referred by the enrollee hotline;
Reporting to the Department:
The resolution of all disputes;
A managed care organization's failure to meet the Department's requirements; and
Any other information specified by the Department;
Educating enrollees about:
The services provided by the enrollee's managed care organization; and
The enrollee's rights and responsibilities in receiving services from the managed care organization; and
Advocating on behalf of the enrollee before the managed care organization, including assisting the enrollee in using the managed care organization's grievance process.
